segments.text: students doing partying and what were they smoking and drinking?
Well, a lot of the students smoked and a lot of them drank and often we would attend parties where there would be a lot of beer or it seems to me I don't drink.
I mean, I didn't drink then.
I seldom drink now and I don't like beer at all.
So, it seems to me that most of them drank beer.
I know my husband drank beer and had nearly had a real
serious accident out on that bridge, going the wrong way on the bridge that didn't exist out there over the river.
And margaritas, I think, they drank margaritas.
And at some of the parties we would have, we'd have cookouts sometimes.
That was the only time that we would entertain each other and have food other than just desserts was hamburgers and hot dogs because that was less expensive.
You said smoking, but they were smoking what?
Just regular tobacco.
Just regular tobacco.
But a lot of them did.
But then I knew a lot of people that didn't smoke and all.
We had friends who lived in, I don't even know whether they do this anymore, but there were a lot of garage apartments around town.
You know, you have to find the, you know, okay, there's the garage upstairs and there's the apartment.
And we had a lot of friends that lived in those kind of situations because people had realized that there weren't enough places for young couples.
Now, as a veterinary student wife, you all didn't go to any of the big dances that year, did you?
Not that year, but I had gone to,
I dated my husband for two years before, and I was here for the senior ring dance when he was a junior.
Describe going to the senior ring dance.
Well, he was an officer that year, and the dance was held, I believe, in Sabisa Hall, and so it was a much, much smaller group of people who were attending it.
It was very formal.
What did you wear?
I wore a long dress.
It was a silk, not brocade, I believe it was a silk, well it was silk anyway.
And it was, you know, he was dressed up in his uniform.
And I believe I even had a tiara on that year.
I think if I look at the picture, I might be able to see it.
And white gloves, you know, the girls with the white gloves.
And we would have a meal.
We had our meal first in the dining hall.
And we had a program with a tassel and very formal.
and then they had the dance right there in Sivisa.
And the orchestra was playing big band music?
Pretty much so, but we're beginning to do, not the Beatles yet, I mean although that was the year that the Beatles were becoming very popular, but rock and roll was also very popular.
was very popular, but it was a lot of big band, but some rock and roll, you know.
I know that my husband had to disappear because he had to do some kind of business for the class, for his class, and so I was there for a while, for a few minutes by myself.
But it was interesting.
I also went to dances that they had at the football games in Dallas and in Fort Worth.
because very often the outfits would have parties and you would, the previous members of the outfit would also attend those, so it was a kind of mixed crowd.
And how were you young ladies treated to those dances?
Very, I mean, I never had any problem with any time the way I was.
I've never had anything but, like most of the guys you say, we treated them like queens.
Right.
I mean, you know, we were honored guests.
And the only thing, I mean, there were occasionally, there were some guys that drank too much.
But generally nothing else happened other than that.
And some guys trying to get home to places where they weren't familiar with it.

you know, five of them were staying in one of their buddies' house in Dallas or in Fort Worth and, you know, they might have gotten lost or they might, I know there was one time when a couple of them ended up sleeping outside in the car because they, once they got home, it was a good thing they got home, but they couldn't get in, so.
But we, but those were, those were interesting parties and they were usually very formal also.
I mean, not that we necessarily wore long dresses, but we did dress up for those, for those parties and,
And I don't remember ever going to one in Houston, but I do remember going to one in Dallas, and I believe one in Fort Worth.
Now, in the 60s, drugs were not even, the words weren't even known, were they?

No, we didn't know anything about drugs, and the campus was very conservative, so I don't think that even though that was the beginning of the change, and I don't think that anybody here would have even thought about that.
In the 60s, did you and your husband even know about the business establishments that supposedly existed over in LaGrange?
I think we probably had heard about that, but not... Do you remember hearing Aggies ever talk about going over there?
I didn't hear anybody specifically talk about that.
I never did either.
That's right.
Because now the legend is growing.
Although you're going to interview my friend and he can tell you about that because I believe he went.
Okay.
Let's see.
We did racial integration and da, da, da, da, da.
And I presume there was no one that you and other co-eds knew was a special person to y'all to turn to for advice?

No, and that was, and looking back, I mean I don't know how many of the other co-eds were like me who were transient and who were going to be here only a year or two because they married somebody who was already
a student here and we're going to leave but they had not made those kind of arrangements for us.
I assume that within a couple of years that they did do that but they just didn't and when I say they the administration was in such a hurry I believe to
go ahead and implement what they decided that they needed to do it.
And even if there were things that got left out, that that was better than not and putting it off.
Because once they did it, I mean, I guess it would be possible to go backwards.
But if they had said, OK, we're going to do it in two years, and we're going to make all these arrangements beforehand, I think there could have been things
And I think that, I mean, you probably know this better than I would, but I would guess that they wanted to do it as quickly as possible so that it couldn't be undone.
Who were the other, as far as you know in that time, who were the other people that really made a difference on this campus?
Well, we talked about Pinky Downs, and he was the spirit raiser.
And I can't think of another specific person, but I know that just as now, the yell leaders were very, very important.
To the boys that were in the Corps, all their outfit leaders were important.
I don't remember talking to any other person that was important to me or that I knew of as far as administrators.
I personally knew that, even though I didn't know him, but that Earl Rudder had made a difference in my life because I was able to come here because of that.
And I did know a few of the people in the vet school at that time.
All right, any other things in your list?
I think I've covered just about everything else that I had talked about because we've gone over the things that I thought were so important.
Silver taps and the muster were very important, and I participated in those since then.
I think the Former Students Association became important to almost every Aggie

also and because you wanted to be a member of the former students association what creates this aggie spirit aggie pride originally i think part of it was because you're different and when you're different that forces you even if you are
have differences among yourself that forces you to be one unit.
And now I think a lot of it has to do with the traditions and the history of A&M.
Which traditions do you think are the most important?
Well, I think muster and silver taps are very important.
I think that there are some things that I think that we need to perhaps look at
I think everybody's looking at him now.

If being in the Corps is causing a student to not be able to succeed academically, then I don't think that the Corps should be, that they should do away with the Corps, but the Corps needs to facilitate the academics, because the students overwhelmingly are here for an education.
I mean, I don't have anything, I think,
like those two are the most important.
I think participating in football games is important.
And even as a graduate student and as a much older graduate student, I went to football games and I stood.
And I always said that I wouldn't stand in the rain, but I did, you know, if it was 85 degrees or 90 degrees, I did that.
So all those kind of things are very important, but I think the things that make us different are muster and silver towels.
What did you learn at A&M that's been important in your life?
Did it have any effect on you, the fact that you had some years here?
I think that being perhaps being part of an institution that is different made me cherish the differences and respect those differences in every way, in every person.
And I think that that's one of the things.
And it made me proud to be an Aggie, and I always wanted to be considered an Aggie.
Even though at this point I don't have a degree from A&M, I always consider myself an Aggie.
Should female Aggies have a different title?
No.
I think that even to consider it, I realize that
In 64 they really didn't know what to do, but there's no difference and we're Aggies.
If you were a consultant to A&M today, what advice would you give them regarding the path to future even greater success?
I think we have to respect everybody's differences.
Although we are proud of our traditions and our history,
and we don't want this not to be Texas A&M.

I think that we have to realize that this is not the same school it was in 1964 or in 1930 and that we have graduate students and that our emphasis in some ways has broadened, not necessarily changed, but we have broadened ourselves and that we have to emphasize that diversity makes us stronger.
Do you have any, my question, if you could make a major gift to A&M, for what purpose would you want that gift used?
Do you have any special interest areas of A&M?
I think that I realized that at one time the library was very lacking.
I must admit that at this point I think that Dean Heath's done a marvelous job over the
10 years or however long he's been here, because I know what it was like before he came.
And I've always encouraged people to make donations to the library.

The other thing that I, the other area that I think is important is, not necessarily because we're going down this road to a school of art, but I think that it's important to know that we do have some fine pieces of art on the campus and to promote that.
Are there any people connected to this institution to whom you feel particularly grateful?
Well, I've already said that I think that Earl Rudder changed my life and because I would have lived a different life if it hadn't been for him.
Other than that, I'm not sure.
I've been mentored recently by some of the administrators.
I've had some wonderful relationships.
Dean Stout is a friend.
has always had time to listen to me.
So there are some other administrators that I think that I stopped and spoke with Bill Perry last week.
Good God.
And I made a suggestion, and he said, well, why don't you take care of it?
I think that one of the things that needs to be done is that the iconography of some of the buildings needs to be researched.
And he said, why don't you talk to Dr. Woodcock about that?
And unfortunately, his project is not going to do that.
But we have some beautiful buildings with some very unusual artwork and I think that it needs to be explained and we need to know why we have these things.
Last things then.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for A&M?
I wanted to come back here.
I chose to come back to A&M in 1995.
And I think that it's a wonderful place to live and I'd be happy to stay here even after I graduate.
So I think A&M is a special place.
I recognize that it's not perfect, but there's not any place that's perfect and I do like A&M and College Station.
And you have to see its strengths and realize, you know, fight to change what needs to be changed.
